-- Regression: REG-02 crash-canary for IRON_HIR_STMT_MATCH.
--
-- **Motivating Incident.** Phase 37-02's collect_mono_enums_node
-- walker in hir_to_lir.c crashed on if/elif/else lowering because its
-- locally-shadowed struct typedef omitted elif fields. The same class
-- of walker incompleteness can re-emerge for any other statement kind
-- -- match in particular carries a condition expression plus a
-- variable-length arm array, so a walker case that fails to recurse
-- into either the scrutinee or any of the arm bodies silently drops
-- the corresponding LIR branches. Phase 66 added -Werror=switch-enum
-- globally to catch missing `case IRON_HIR_STMT_MATCH:` at compile
-- time; this canary is the runtime regression net for walker cases
-- that handle the case header but mis-recurse into the payload.
--
-- **Layout Diagram.** Iron_MatchStmt carries
--   { span, kind, scrutinee, arms[], arm_count, default_arm }
-- where each arm carries { pattern, binders[], body }. Walker cases
-- that fail to recurse into the arm array silently drop the bodies
-- from the lowered LIR; cases that fail to recurse into the scrutinee
-- drop the match target expression entirely.
--
-- **Fix Summary.** Phase 67-08 added this fixture as a REG-02 crash
-- canary. Exercises a simple 4-arm integer match over a helper
-- function's return value, verifies the sum of all arm results.
-- CI integration: runs in both Debug and Release via Phase 66-04's
-- build-and-test-release job.
--
-- **Severity.** H (regression potential) -- match is the second most
-- frequent control-flow statement after IF in Iron source code, so
-- any walker regression here turns most real programs red immediately.

func describe(n: Int) -> Int {
  match n {
    1 -> return 10
    2 -> return 20
    3 -> return 30
    else -> return 99
  }
  return 0
}

func main() {
  var total = 0
  total = total + describe(1)   -- 10
  total = total + describe(2)   -- 20
  total = total + describe(3)   -- 30
  total = total + describe(7)   -- 99
  println("total: {total}")
}
